{"parentUuid":"ec579d3b-188f-40e0-b9ab-95d3043d3b3a","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aa041f3ac0f60e829","message":{"id":"resp_0a4cf7697020dbeb0169b9a1db852c8199aa16dbfb3888ba59","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"gpt-5.4","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0},"content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"call_xaQyr22790ZdD06BIX0UhVfT","name":"mcp__sequential-thinking__sequentialthinking","input":{"thought":"I need to compare three QA items in an older improvement backlog file against three later refactor specs, with special attention to BLOCKED semantics and state enum interactions across sprint/executor.py, pipeline/models.py, and sprint/models.py. I should first gather detailed evidence from the files, then classify each item as REDUNDANT, CONTRADICTED, OVERLAPPING, or UNAFFECTED, and provide precise recommendations.","thoughtNumber":1,"totalThoughts":4,"nextThoughtNeeded":true}}],"stop_reason":null},"type":"assistant","uuid":"d18c0c90-1182-4c1f-bcf6-f745a82f8970","timestamp":"2026-03-17T18:48:06.782Z","userType":"external","cwd":"/config/workspace/IronClaude","sessionId":"caf57f20-b6f0-47d7-a404-b3840c9c44e5","version":"2.1.77","gitBranch":"v3.0-AuditGates","slug":"bright-juggling-reef"}
{"parentUuid":"1087685d-b318-46c4-8696-a2c62e8a919e","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aa041f3ac0f60e829","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_hnSBzG9pWjAFSfQVhmvkzieu","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The following code sections were retrieved:\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/improve-quality-agents.md\n     1\t---\n     2\tcomponent: quality-agents\n     3\tdeliverable: D-0026\n     4\tsource_comparison: comparison-quality-agents.md\n     5\tverdict: split by context\n     6\tprinciple_primary: Scalable Quality Enforcement\n     7\tprinciple_secondary: Evidence Integrity\n     8\tgenerated: 2026-03-15\n     9\t---\n    10\t\n    11\t# Improvement Plan: Quality Agents\n    12\t\n    13\tTraceability source: D-0022 merged-strategy.md. All items trace to one or more of the five architectural principles.\n    14\t\n    15\t---\n    16\t\n    17\t## ITEM QA-001 — Executor Validation Gate for All Agent Entry Points\n    18\t\n    19\t**Priority**: P0\n    20\t**Effort**: S\n    21\t**Classification**: strengthen existing code\n    22\t**patterns_not_mass**: true — adopting LW's executor validation gate pattern (validate input before starting execution, emit BLOCKED for invalid input) without LW's permissionMode:bypassPermissions\n    23\t**Why not full import**: LW's validation gate is bundled with `permissionMode: bypassPermissions` for rf-* agents (explicitly rejected in D-0022 Principle 4); IC's validation gate must be the inverse — validate first and block on invalid input, without bypassing permissions.\n    24\t\n    25\t**File paths and change description**:\n    26\t- `.claude/agents/quality-engineer.md` — Add to the agent's operating instructions: \"Before beginning any verification task, validate that the task specification includes: (a) an explicit acceptance criteria list, (b) at least one file path reference, (c) a compliance tier. If any of these is absent, emit BLOCKED with reason and request the missing fields before proceeding.\"\n    27\t- `src/superclaude/agents/quality-engineer.md` — Sync copy.\n    28\t- `.claude/agents/self-review.md` — Add the same pre-execution validation checklist: validate that the implementation record includes at least one artifact path and a stated completion claim.\n    29\t- `src/superclaude/agents/self-review.md` — Sync copy.\n    30\t- `.claude/agents/audit-validator.md` — Confirm this agent already has `permissionMode: plan` (read-only). Add: \"If the sample of audit findings provided has fewer than 3 items, emit BLOCKED with reason 'insufficient sample size for validation' rather than producing an unreliable PASS.\"\n    31\t\n    32\t**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 5 (Scalable Quality Enforcement), direction 6: \"Before any agent begins execution, it should validate its input file/specification and emit BLOCKED if the structure is invalid.\"\n...\n    47\t\n    48\t**File paths and change description**:\n    49\t- `src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/models.py` — Add `AgentHandoffState` enum: `TASK_READY`, `EXECUTION_COMPLETE`, `BLOCKED`, `VALIDATED`. This enum is used by pipeline code that invokes agents sequentially (quality-engineer verification, audit pass progression).\n    50\t- `src/superclaude/cli/sprint/executor.py` — At quality-engineer agent invocation sites (STRICT-tier task verification), emit `AgentHandoffState.TASK_READY` before invocation and `AgentHandoffState.EXECUTION_COMPLETE` or `AgentHandoffState.BLOCKED` after. Log these transitions to the sprint result file.\n    51\t- `.claude/agents/pm-agent.md` — Document the typed handoff states: \"When delegating to quality-engineer, set state to TASK_READY. After quality-engineer returns, check for BLOCKED state before proceeding.\"\n    52\t- `src/superclaude/agents/pm-agent.md` — Sync copy.\n    53\t\n    54\t**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 5 (Scalable Quality Enforcement), direction 5: \"For IC components that involve sequential agent invocation, adopt explicit typed state transitions. BLOCKED as a first-class message type prevents silent failures in agent coordination.\"\n    55\t\n    56\t**Dependencies**: QA-001 (BLOCKED state from validation gate must use the same enum)\n    57\t**Acceptance criteria**: `AgentHandoffState` enum exists in models.py; sprint executor emits TASK_READY before quality-engineer invocation; BLOCKED state is emitted when agent cannot proceed; pm-agent.md documents handoff states.\n    58\t**Risk**: Medium. New enum and emission logic in sprint executor; requires integration test verifying state transitions are logged correctly.\n    59\t\n    60\t---\n    61\t\n    62\t## ITEM QA-003 — Model Tier Proportionality Policy for Quality Agents\n...\n    69\t\n    70\t**File paths and change description**:\n    71\t- `.claude/agents/quality-engineer.md` — Add \"Model Tier Policy\": \"quality-engineer runs at Sonnet tier. Escalation to Opus tier is permitted only when: (a) STRICT-tier task involves cross-component dependency analysis spanning >5 files, or (b) security domain path (auth/, crypto/) is involved. Haiku tier is not appropriate for quality-engineer (insufficient depth for STRICT verification).\"\n    72\t- `src/superclaude/agents/quality-engineer.md` — Sync copy.\n    73\t- `.claude/agents/audit-validator.md` — Add \"Model Tier Policy\": \"audit-validator uses Haiku tier (10% spot-check validation; Sonnet-level depth is not required for random sampling).\"\n    74\t- `src/superclaude/agents/audit-validator.md` — Sync copy.\n    75\t- `.claude/agents/self-review.md` — Add \"Model Tier Policy\": \"self-review uses Haiku tier for routine 4-question post-implementation checks; escalate to Sonnet for STRICT-tier implementation reviews.\"\n    76\t- `src/superclaude/agents/self-review.md` — Sync copy.\n    77\t\n    78\t**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 4 (Bounded Complexity), direction 1: \"IC's tiered model selection should be formalized into an explicit model-selection policy. The audit-validator (10% spot-check) should not use the same model as quality-engineer (STRICT-tier deep verification).\"\n    79\t\n    80\t**Dependencies**: None\n    81\t**Acceptance criteria**: All three agent .md files (quality-engineer, audit-validator, self-review) have a \"Model Tier Policy\" section; each specifies a primary tier and explicit escalation conditions; all dev copies are synced.\n    82\t**Risk**: Low. Documentation only; no behavioral change.\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/strategy-ic-quality-agents.md\n     1\t---\n     2\tcomponent: quality-agents\n     3\tframework: IronClaude\n     4\tphase: 3\n     5\tgenerated: 2026-03-14\n     6\tevidence_source: auggie-mcp\n     7\t---\n     8\t\n     9\t# Strategy: IronClaude Quality Agents\n    10\t\n    11\t## 1. Design Philosophy\n    12\t\n    13\tThe quality agents group exists to provide independent, specialized quality verification at different granularities: task-level (quality-engineer), audit-level (audit-validator), implementation-level (self-review), and session-level (pm-agent). The core design principle is **agent-as-verifier independence** — each quality agent is explicitly prohibited from assuming the prior agent's output is correct, and must verify claims from scratch.\n...\n    20\t\n    21\t**quality-engineer**: Invoked via `Task` tool for STRICT-tier verification in `sc:task-unified`. Performs: requirement analysis, test case design, test prioritization by risk, automated test framework setup, and quality risk assessment. Outputs: test strategy, test cases, automated test suites, quality assessment reports. Behavioral mindset: \"think beyond the happy path to discover hidden failure modes\" (`.claude/agents/quality-engineer.md:15`).\n    22\t\n    23\t**audit-validator**: Receives a 10% stratified sample of cleanup-audit findings. Runs 4-check verification methodology:\n    24\t1. Did the primary agent actually read the files cited?\n    25\t2. Do grep claims match reality?\n    26\t3. Are classifications correct?\n    27\t4. Are DELETE recommendations safe (no false negatives on live files)?\n...\n    46\t\n    47\t**Trade-off**: The `quality-engineer` agent is invoked only for STRICT-tier tasks. STANDARD-tier tasks receive only direct test execution (no quality agent). This means a STANDARD-tier task with 3 affected files and non-trivial logic receives less verification than it might warrant — the tier classification is the sole determinant of whether quality-engineer is invoked.\n    48\t\n    49\t## 4. Error Handling Strategy\n    50\t\n    51\t**Verification failure escalation**: If `quality-engineer` produces a quality assessment report identifying critical risks, the result is returned to the orchestrating agent with the assessment inline. The orchestrating agent must decide how to proceed — there is no automatic rollback or halt mechanism in the quality agent itself.\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/comparison-quality-agents.md\n     1\t---\n     2\tcomparison_pair: 6\n     3\tic_component: Quality Agents\n     4\tlw_component: Agent Definitions (rf-*.md)\n     5\tic_source: .claude/agents/quality-engineer.md, .claude/agents/audit-validator.md, src/superclaude/agents/pm-agent.md\n     6\tlw_source: .claude/agents/rf-team-lead.md, .claude/agents/rf-task-builder.md, .claude/agents/rf-task-executor.md, .claude/agents/rf-task-researcher.md\n     7\tmapping_type: direct\n     8\tverdict_class: split by context\n     9\tconfidence: 0.79\n    10\tpatterns_not_mass_verified: true\n    11\tgenerated: 2026-03-15\n    12\t---\n    13\t\n    14\t# Adversarial Comparison: Quality Agents (IC) vs Agent Definitions / rf-* (LW)\n    15\t\n    16\t## 1. Debating Positions\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.5RigorFlowMerger/improve-adversarial-pipeline.md\n...\n    24\t\n    25\t**File paths and change description**:\n    26\t- `.claude/agents/quality-engineer.md` — Add a \"Sycophancy Detection NFR\" section with: the 12-category taxonomy (immediate agreement, validation seeking, context abandonment, etc.) and the non-linear multiplier rule (1.0× for 1 pattern, 1.3× for 2 patterns, 1.5× for 3+ patterns). Add the four-tier response routing: score < 1.0 → standard response; 1.0–1.3 → explicitly present trade-offs; 1.3–1.5 → escalate to adversarial check; > 1.5 → challenge the premise.\n    27\t- `src/superclaude/agents/quality-engineer.md` — Sync copy.\n    28\t- `.claude/agents/self-review.md` — Add the same Sycophancy Detection NFR section (self-review agent is the most susceptible to sycophantic affirmations of the implementer's own work).\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.0_fidelity-refactor_/wiring-verification-gate-v1.0-release-spec.md\n     1\t---\n     2\trelease: wiring-verification-gate-v1.0\n     3\tversion: 1.0.0\n     4\tstatus: draft\n     5\tdate: 2026-03-17\n     6\tparent_analysis: cli-portify-executor-noop-forensic-report.md\n     7\tparent_ranking: proposal-ranking.md\n     8\tfidelity_link: \"Link 3: Tasklist -> Code\"\n     9\tpriority: P0\n    10\testimated_scope: 300-400 lines production code\n    11\t---\n    12\t\n    13\t# Wiring Verification Gate v1.0 -- Release Specification\n    14\t\n    15\t## 1. Problem Statement\n...\n    39\t\n    40\t1. Detect unwired injectable dependencies (`Optional[Callable] = None` never provided at any call site)\n    41\t2. Detect orphan modules (exported functions never imported by any consumer)\n    42\t3. Detect unwired dispatch registries (dictionary entries mapping to non-importable functions)\n    43\t4. Emit a structured YAML report compatible with the `GateCriteria`/`SemanticCheck` pattern\n    44\t5. Deploy in shadow mode initially, with a path to soft and full enforcement\n    45\t\n    46\t### Non-Goals (v1.0)\n...\n   387\t```\n   388\t\n   389\t### 4.3 Report Format\n   390\t\n   391\tThe wiring analysis emits a Markdown file with YAML frontmatter, conforming to\n   392\tthe `GateCriteria` validation pattern used by all existing gates.\n   393\t\n   394\t```markdown\n   395\t---\n   396\tgate: wiring-verification\n   397\ttarget_dir: src/superclaude/cli/cli_portify\n   398\tfiles_analyzed: 14\n   399\tunwired_count: 1\n   400\torphan_count: 2\n   401\tregistry_count: 0\n   402\ttotal_findings: 3\n   403\tanalysis_complete: true\n   404\tenforcement_mode: shadow\n   405\t---\n   406\t\n   407\t# Wiring Verification Report\n   408\t\n   409\t## Unwired Callables (1)\n   410\t\n   411\t### WF-001: PortifyExecutor.step_runner\n...\n   689\t\n   690\t| Field | Type | Constraint |\n   691\t|-------|------|-----------|\n   692\t| `gate` | string | Must be `\"wiring-verification\"` |\n   693\t| `target_dir` | string | Non-empty |\n   694\t| `files_analyzed` | int | >= 0 |\n   695\t| `unwired_count` | int | Must be 0 for gate pass |\n   696\t| `orphan_count` | int | Must be 0 for gate pass |\n   697\t| `registry_count` | int | Must be 0 for gate pass |\n   698\t| `total_findings` | int | Must equal sum of above three |\n   699\t| `analysis_complete` | bool | Must be true |\n   700\t| `whitelist_entries_applied` | int | >= 0; count of whitelist entries that suppressed findings |\n   701\t\n   702\t---\n   703\t\n   704\t## 7. Risk Assessment\n...\n   867\t\n   868\t| SC | Description | Verification |\n   869\t|----|-------------|-------------|\n   870\t| SC-001 | Wiring gate detects `Optional[Callable] = None` never provided at call site | Unit test: `test_detect_unwired_callable_basic` |\n   871\t| SC-002 | Wiring gate detects orphan modules in `steps/` directories | Unit test: `test_detect_orphan_module` |\n   872\t| SC-003 | Wiring gate detects unresolvable registry entries | Unit test: `test_detect_unwired_registry` |\n   873\t| SC-004 | Report conforms to `GateCriteria` validation pattern | Unit test: `test_gate_passes_clean_report` |\n   874\t| SC-005 | `gate_passed()` evaluates `WIRING_GATE` without modification | Integration test: `test_cli_portify_fixture` |\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.05_Anti-instincts_/anti-instincts-gate-unified.md\n...\n   110\t\n   111\tA deterministic, regex-based post-generation pass that scans the merged roadmap for scaffolding terms and verifies each has a corresponding discharge task in a later phase. Catches the failure mode where early phases use \"mocked\", \"stub\", \"skeleton\", \"placeholder\" language that creates implicit obligations that later phases never fulfill.\n   112\t\n   113\t### Detection Axis\n   114\t\n   115\tV2-A's obligation scanner detects a fundamentally different failure mode than omission-based approaches. Rather than checking whether a requirement is present, it checks whether deferred commitments are fulfilled. This catches bugs where the requirement IS mentioned (as scaffolding) but the follow-through is missing.\n   116\t\n   117\t### Implementation\n...\n   947\t\n   948\t### Enforcement Strategy\n   949\t\n   950\t<!-- Source: V1-C (spec structural audit), adapted per refactor-plan -->\n   951\t\n   952\tPhase 1 (immediate): Warning-only. The executor logs a warning if the ratio falls below 0.5 but does not block the pipeline. This allows shadow-mode validation on real specs before enforcement.\n   953\t\n   954\tPhase 2 (after validation): STRICT enforcement. If the structural count suggests the extraction is missing significant content, the executor re-triggers extraction or halts with an actionable error.\n   955\t\n   956\t---\n   957\t\n   958\t## 8. Gate Definition\n   959\t\n   960\t<!-- Source: Merge (new content bridging V2+V5) -->\n   961\t\n   962\t### New Gate: `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE`\n   963\t\n   964\t**File**: `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/gates.py` (modify existing)\n   965\t\n   966\t```python\n   967\t# --- Anti-Instinct Gate check functions ---\n...\n  1069\t```\n  1070\t\n  1071\t### Why a Separate Gate\n  1072\t\n  1073\t<!-- Source: Merge (new content bridging V2+V5) -->\n  1074\t\n  1075\tThe `MERGE_GATE` validates the merge step's output quality (heading hierarchy, cross-refs, duplicates). The anti-instinct checks validate cross-artifact semantic fidelity -- a different concern. Keeping them separate follows the existing pattern where each gate corresponds to one validation concern. The `MERGE_GATE` runs on the merged roadmap; the `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE` runs on the anti-instinct audit report produced by the executor.\n  1076\t\n  1077\t### Anti-Instinct Audit Report Format\n  1078\t\n  1079\tThe executor produces `output_dir / \"anti-instinct-audit.md\"` with frontmatter:\n...\n  1395\t\n  1396\t| File | Changes | Source |\n  1397\t|---|---|---|\n  1398\t| `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/gates.py` | Add `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE` definition with 3 semantic checks; add 3 check functions (`_no_undischarged_obligations`, `_integration_contracts_covered`, `_fingerprint_coverage_check`); update `ALL_GATES` list to insert `(\"anti-instinct\", ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE)` between `merge` and `test-strategy` | V2-A + V5-1 + V4-2 |\n  1399\t| `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/executor.py` | Add anti-instinct step to `_build_steps()`; add structural audit hook after extract (`_run_structural_audit`); add `_run_anti_instinct_audit()` function; add import for `ANTI_INSTINCT_GATE`; update `_get_all_step_ids()` to include `\"anti-instinct\"` | All |\n...\n\nPath: .dev/releases/backlog/v3.1_unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1/unified-audit-gating-v1.2.1-release-spec.md\n...\n    16\t\n    17\t### 0.3 Citation rule used\n    18\tCritical claims cite source file + section label. If section labels are absent, file heading context is used.\n    19\t\n    20\t---\n    21\t\n    22\t## 1. Release Scope and Goals\n    23\t\n    24\t### 1.1 Scope\n    25\tImplement a unified audit-gating capability that blocks completion/release transitions unless the corresponding gate passes at three scopes:\n    26\t1. Task gate\n    27\t2. Milestone gate\n    28\t3. Release gate\n    29\t\n    30\t(Source: `01-requirements-spec.md` → Goal; Task-Level Gate; Milestone-Level Gate; Release-Level Gate)\n    31\t\n    32\t### 1.2 Primary goals\n    33\t1. Deterministic pass/fail gating with evidence-backed outputs\n    34\t2. Explicit audit workflow states for all scopes\n    35\t3. Single primary user interface (`/sc:audit-gate`)\n    36\t4. Rollout-safe enforcement (shadow → soft → full)\n...\n   180\t\n   181\t(Source: `01-requirements-spec.md` → Reporting + Non-Functional Requirements; `04-design-v1.1-delta-handoff.md` → GateResult schema)\n   182\t\n   183\t---\n   184\t\n   185\t## 6. Data Contracts and Versioning\n   186\t\n   187\t### 6.1 GateResult (normative v1.2.1)\n   188\tRequired fields:\n   189\t- `version`\n   190\t- `gate_run_id`\n   191\t- `scope`, `entity_id`, `profile`\n   192\t- `status`, `score`, `threshold`\n   193\t- `checks[]` (includes severity + evidence)\n   194\t- `drift_summary` (`edited`, `non_edited`)\n   195\t- `override` block\n   196\t- `timing` block\n   197\t- `artifacts` block\n   198\t- `failure_class` (v1.2 addition)\n   199\t\n   200\t(Source: `04-design-v1.1-delta-handoff.md` → Canonical GateResult; `design-delta-v1.2.md` → Add 2)\n...\n   260\t\n   261\t(Source: `metrics-and-gates.md`; `risk-register-v1.2.md` R1/R2/R8/R10; `design-delta-v1.2.md` Add 5)\n   262\t\n   263\t---\n   264\t\n   265\t## 8. KPI/SLO Framework\n   266\t\n   267\t### 8.1 Provisional vs normative thresholds\n   268\t- Thresholds in current KPI table are **provisional** in shadow mode.\n   269\t- They become **normative** only after calibration and explicit approval at phase gate.\n   270\t\n   271\t(Source: `metrics-and-gates.md` → KPI/SLO table note)\n   272\t\n   273\t### 8.2 Calibration method (normative)\n   274\t1. Collect M1–M12 for at least two shadow windows.\n   275\t2. Compute baseline distributions and replay stability.\n   276\t3. Propose thresholds and warning/fail bands.\n   277\t4. Obtain owner sign-off for normative activation at soft/full gate.\n   278\t\n   279\t(Source: `metrics-and-gates.md` → Shadow and phase gates)\n...\n   418\t\n   419\t## Top 5 Immediate Actions\n   420\t1. Finalize and sign off profile thresholds + major-severity behavior.\n   421\t2. Finalize retry/backoff/timeout and stale-state budgets.\n   422\t3. Ratify explicit legal/illegal transition table as implementation authority.\n   423\t4. Approve rollback/safe-disable triggers and phase regression policy.\n   424\t5. Assign owner + UTC deadline + effective phase to each blocking decision.\n   425\t\n   426\t## Top 5 Deferred Improvements\n   427\t1. Add readiness preview mode pre-gate.\n   428\t2. Improve human-readable remediation hints in gate failures.\n   429\t3. Add trend dashboards for drift/override quality.\n   430\t4. Add profile auto-tuning recommendations from shadow telemetry.\n   431\t5. Optimize long-horizon artifact retention policy.\n...\n\n"}]}]},"uuid":"eb0d957b-d5d8-4536-8ca8-b790b0069c11","timestamp":"2026-03-17T18:48:10.916Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"1087685d-b318-46c4-8696-a2c62e8a919e","userType":"external","cwd":"/config/workspace/IronClaude","sessionId":"caf57f20-b6f0-47d7-a404-b3840c9c44e5","version":"2.1.77","gitBranch":"v3.0-AuditGates","slug":"bright-juggling-reef"}
