{"parentUuid":"d9104cc3-06a9-4a71-9a09-d8afd73711c5","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aa041f3ac0f60e829","message":{"id":"resp_01cc11c35455156a0169b9a218a300819a83dbee4856706ccc","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"gpt-5.4","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":51130,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":3584,"output_tokens":744,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"call_47r277OfwgiZdIYv9zw4UtUa","name":"mcp__sequential-thinking__sequentialthinking","input":{"thought":"Final classifications should distinguish semantic alignment from implementation conflict. QA-001 is not replaced outright: its pre-execution validation and fail-fast behavior are still useful, but v3.1 formalizes gate outcomes as passed/failed with failure_class taxonomy and explicit audit_* states, so raw BLOCKED wording should be revised to map into that contract. QA-002 is the strongest conflict: it proposes a parallel state enum in pipeline/models.py and sprint/executor.py, while v3.1 designates sprint/models.py as the authoritative home for states/enums and defines a full legal transition table plus GateTransitionEvent schema; introducing AgentHandoffState would create competing vocabularies (TASK_READY/EXECUTION_COMPLETE/BLOCKED/VALIDATED vs ready_for_audit_task/audit_task_running/audit_task_passed|failed). QA-003 remains independent because none of the three refactors define model-tier policy for quality agents.","thoughtNumber":3,"totalThoughts":4,"nextThoughtNeeded":false}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use"},"type":"assistant","uuid":"b7fbf556-8db2-4dc6-a0d5-4989d02ad2db","timestamp":"2026-03-17T18:49:17.668Z","userType":"external","cwd":"/config/workspace/IronClaude","sessionId":"caf57f20-b6f0-47d7-a404-b3840c9c44e5","version":"2.1.77","gitBranch